I see a couple of places where the unwanted domains could possibly be getti=
ng included. In your SurtPrefixedDecideRule there is &lt;property name=3D&quot;seed=
sAsSurtPrefixes&quot; value=3D&quot;true&quot; /&gt;. If you have any seeds in your seed list=
 that are http://www.example.com/* or http://bike.example.com/* this would =
make their surt prefixes acceptable and rule in urls from the domains &quot;www.=
example.com&quot; or &quot;bike.example.com.&quot; If you think this is the problem, you c=
ould uncomment that &quot;seedsAsSurtPrefixes&quot; property and set it to &quot;false&quot;. 
=

Another rule you have that allows the crawler to download from other domai=
ns than what you specifically set is the TransclusionDecideRule. This accep=
ts URIs that are found as embedded links (images, javascript, css)  in your=
 accepted pages even if they would otherwise be rejected. So if a page  you=
 do want has an image from somewhere like at http://www.example.com/*, the =
image would be downloaded. If you think this is the cause and you don&#39;t wan=
t this behavior, you could remove the TransclusionDecideRule from your rule=
 list, but keep in mind that will affect the way downloaded pages will appe=
ar when replayed.

Also there is a typo in this surt prefix:
+http://(come,=
baidu,zhidao,)/question
with the &quot;e&quot; on com, but that shouldn&#39;t cause your =
current problem.

